def basic_details(df):
    no_obs = df.shape[0]
    column_names = df.columns
    types = df.dtypes
    unique_values = df.apply(lambda x : [x.unique()])
    nulls = df.apply(lambda x : x.isnull().sum())
    distinct_values = df.apply(lambda x: x.unique().shape[0])
    missing_ration = df.apply(lambda x : (x.isnull().sum()/no_obs)*100 )
    skewness = df.skew()
    kurtosis = df.kurt()
    print('Shape:', df.shape)
    
    print(df.info())
    
    details_df = pd.concat([types, distinct_values, nulls, missing_ration, unique_values, skewness, kurtosis], axis=1)
    
    column_names = ['dtype','distincts','nulls','missing ration','uniques','skewness','kurtosis']
    details_df.columns = column_names
    
    return details_df

    But, in the given Dataset, there are very high number of samples with quality value - 5,6,7 and
    very low number of samples with quality value-3,9. We can observe that the Dataset is highly unbalanced.

2. We cannot use MLR. Instead we have to go for Non-Linear Mothods.

Observations:

1.We saw both in the form of visualization (Bivariate Graphs) and Correlation matrix that
  Density has strong positive correlation with Residual Sugar and strong negative correlation with Alcohol%.`
2.Hence including such variable in linear regression model would violate the multicollinearity assumption.

Remedies:

1.Remove highly correlated variables
2.Use linear combination of correlated variables/ apply PCA.

Since the data has only 9 independent variables, removing some of them will result in loss of information. Hence, I have applied PCA to overcome multicollinearity problem and it also helps in retaining much of the information. Following are the results:

Principal Component Analysis - PCA¶

from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

# pca_data = data.drop(data.index[2781])

cols = pca_data.columns
